  abstract = {Abstract Direct numerical simulation of the gravity-induced settling of finite-size particles in triply periodic domains has been performed under dilute conditions. For a single solid-to-fluid-density ratio of 1.5 we have considered two values of the Galileo number corresponding to steady vertical motion ( \textbackslash textbackslash def \textbackslash textbackslash xmlpi \#1\textbackslash textbraceleft\textbackslash textbraceright\textbackslash textbackslash def \textbackslash textbackslash mathsfbi \#1\textbackslash textbraceleft\textbackslash textbackslash boldsymbol \textbackslash textbraceleft\textbackslash textbackslash mathsf \textbackslash textbraceleft\#1\textbackslash textbraceright\textbackslash textbraceright\textbackslash textbraceright\textbackslash textbackslash let \textbackslash textbackslash le =\textbackslash textbackslash leqslant \textbackslash textbackslash let \textbackslash textbackslash leq =\textbackslash textbackslash leqslant \textbackslash textbackslash let \textbackslash textbackslash ge =\textbackslash textbackslash geqslant \textbackslash textbackslash let \textbackslash textbackslash geq =\textbackslash textbackslash geqslant \textbackslash textbackslash def \textbackslash textbackslash Pr \textbackslash textbraceleft\textbackslash textbackslash mathit \textbackslash textbraceleft Pr\textbackslash textbraceright\textbackslash textbraceright\textbackslash textbackslash def \textbackslash textbackslash Fr \textbackslash textbraceleft\textbackslash textbackslash mathit \textbackslash textbraceleft Fr\textbackslash textbraceright\textbackslash textbraceright\textbackslash textbackslash def \textbackslash textbackslash Rey \textbackslash textbraceleft\textbackslash textbackslash mathit \textbackslash textbraceleft Re\textbackslash textbraceright\textbackslash textbraceright\textbackslash textbackslash mathit\textbackslash textbraceleft Ga\textbackslash textbraceright =121\textbackslash{} ) and to steady oblique motion ( \textbackslash textbackslash mathit\textbackslash textbraceleft Ga\textbackslash textbraceright =178\textbackslash{} ) in the case of one isolated sphere. For the multiparticle system we observe strong particle clustering only in the latter case. The geometry and time scales related to clustering are determined from Voronoï tessellation and particle-conditioned averaging. As a consequence of clustering, the average particle settling velocity is increased by 12 \% as compared with the value of an isolated sphere; such a collective effect is not observed in the non-clustering case. By defining a local (instantaneous) fluid velocity average in the vicinity of the finite-size particles it is shown that the observed enhancement of the settling velocity is due to the fact that the downward fluid motion (with respect to the global average) which is induced in the cluster regions is preferentially sampled by the particles. It is further observed that the variance of the particle velocity is strongly enhanced in the clustering case. With the aid of a decomposition of the particle velocity it is shown that this increase is due to enhanced fluid velocity fluctuations (due to clustering) in the vicinity of the particles. Finally, we discuss a possible explanation for the observation of a critical Galileo number marking the onset of clustering under dilute conditions.},
  file = {/home/nejcv/Zotero/storage/HEB8JXXP/Uhlmann and Doychev - 2014 - Sedimentation of a dilute suspension of rigid spheres at intermediate Galileo numbers the effect of.pdf}
}

